<h1 class="text-center">Do you need skateboarding shoes?</h1>
<p>
  Short answer:<span class="bold"> YES, you do.</span>
</p>

<p>
  Many people starting out in skateboarding think that skateboarding shoes are not necessary. </p>

<p>
  Although you can skate with any shoe, using skateboarding shoes <span class="bold">will help you learn much faster </span>.
</p>

<br>
<h5 class="bold">What skateboarding shoe should I buy?</h5>
<p class="subtitle">Here are some guiding points:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Make sure its meant to be a skateboarding shoe. For example, Nike's skateboarding shoes are tagged with 'SB' for skateboarding.</li>
  <li>If you want great board feeling, pick thin shoes such as Vans Slip Ons.
    They will rip quickly - but they give great board feeling for the time that they last.
  </li>
  <li>If you want safety, pick thicker shoes with heel support.
    <img alt="skateboarding shoe" src="https://res.cloudinary.com/diopgwo4d/image/upload/v1620202768/0f6a57eeb6f44c12af8c156e7d7904f6-removebg-preview_gekpgc.png" class="img-small center-img" style="margin-top:-150px;">
    <p style="margin-top:-150px;">As you can see in the shoe above, the sole is thick and acts as extra support.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    A good add-on are extra insoles such as <a href="https://www.fpinsoles.com/every-foot-is-different/" target="_blank">FP insoles</a> that provide extra protection</li>
  </li>
  <li>Because of the skateboard's griptape, shoes will rip. There are no shoes that will last forever. Something you can do though is use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoe_Goo" target="_blank">Shoe Goo</a>. Add this glue to the stitches
  of your shoe and it will last much longer.</li>
</ul>

